				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">The <a href="http://n64.icequake.net/mirror/www.crazynation.org/N64/" class="postlink">icequake/crazynation mirror</a> does actually have enough information, although it's a little obtuse.<br /><br />Basically:<br />Multiplexed 16-bit wide bus.<br />Byte access is <em>not</em> supported.<br />Address is 32 bits wide, and specifies a <em>byte</em> offset, even though the bus is not byte-addressable. (i.e. ignore the contents of A0)<br />Upper 16 and lower 16 bits of address bus go through two transparent latches inside the ROM, effectively latching the address on a falling edge of ALE_H or ALE_L.<br />A rising edge of /RD or /WR automatically adds 2 (i.e 16-bit aligned) to the current address. There are 8 bits of this behavior. (i.e. A1 through A8)<br /><br /><a href="http://assemblergames.com/l/threads/reflashing-or-making-reproduction-n64-carts.61695/#post-883560" class="postlink">This flashable board</a> uses a pile of 74-series parts with an ordinary 3V flash ROM. It's good enough for any of the save-less games.<br /><br />The N64 bootstrap expects to be able to read from the cart ROM starting at address 0x1000_0000. I think I remember reading that it reads a few bytes, setting properties of the Parallel Interface (the name for the cart/expansion port), then loads the first 4 KiB somewhere... and I think that in turn loads the first 1 MiB into RDRAM and the game &quot;really&quot; starts.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

